(177) From the point of view of their function or meaning, compounds may be distinguished as copulative, deter- minative and possessive.

I. A copulative compound is one in which neither oi the terms determines the meaning of the other, but both, being placed as it were on the same footing, retain in composition the meaning and the function which they would have if used separately. This class, which has been immensely developed in Sanskrit, cy. dual Mitto-caratiae (Mitra and Varuna) has scarcely any representatives in Greek: νυχθ-ήμερον (night and day), popo-rrteot-rppos (ointment made oi scented cil, pitoh, and wax).¹ In Latin we may quote scote-taurana (solemn sacrifice of oswine, a sheep, and a bull).
